 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are given a text input that describes a user request typically issued to a digital assistant or smart device. Your task is to classify the text into one of the following intent categories:\n\nalarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nClassify each text according to the *main* action or intent that it describes, not just based on the presence of certain keywords. Carefully consider the context and implied action, especially in cases where an instruction may overlap multiple domains.\n\n* For requests involving reminders or scheduled actions (such as \"remind me to pay the electricity bill on Saturday at nine am\"), classify as 'calendar_set', not 'lists_createoradd', even if the note resembles a list item.\n* If the text is about creating or adding items to a list (e.g., shopping or to-do list), use 'lists_createoradd'.\n* Choose the most specific label: prefer action-based categories (e.g., calendar_set, alarm_set) over general or passive categories (e.g., lists_createoradd) when scheduling or timed actions are involved.\n* For each task, output only the exact name of the category from the provided list.\n\nUse your domain knowledge to correctly interpret user intent based on both explicit and implicit instructions, with attention to contextual cues and nuanced differences between list management and scheduling/reminder tasks."
 },
